Every time I speak in front of an audience, whatever I say, there are social media blunders calling for my candidacy to be rejected as a Member of Parliament for the next election, exposing the politics of the centre and telling me that I should not be a member of Labour.
And that's just what I'm going through.
Indeed, I know that I am more fortunate than some of my colleagues, because the comments on my address are generally political.
I am impressed by the professionalism and determination of those colleagues who have to deal with a flood of sexist or racist reactions every day, but do not let themselves be intimidated.
One of the most disappointing aspects of this era of politics is that bad slurs are apparently considered normal.
Jeremy Corbyn claimed last week that the Labour Party should promote a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that we are no longer that broad church and with every ‘motion of distrust’ or change of selection rules the party becomes more petty.
For the past two years, I have often been advised to keep my mouth shut, not just to speak my mind out loud, and then I would ‘not get in trouble’.
But I didn’t go into politics for that.
Since I joined Labour 32 years ago as a school child, provoked by the neglect of the Thatcher government that literally collapsed my classroom, I have always advocated better public services for those who need them most, both in my role as a councillor and in my role as a minister.
I have never kept my politics hidden, not even in the last election.
Everyone in Nottingham East had clarity about my policy positions and my points of disagreement with the current leadership.
To those who voted for the motion on Friday, I can only say one thing: when the country moves towards a Brexit that will harm families, businesses and our public services, I do not understand the desire to waste time and energy on my loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But actually I have only one message, and that is not addressed to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are members of Labour or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that threats to reject my candidacy as a Member of Parliament for the next election or political opportunities will not deter me from doing so.
