North Korea says it will “under no circumstances” unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the ongoing sanctions are leading to growing mistrust in the United States and that under such circumstances the country could not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site, and vowing not to distribute nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“We don’t see a corresponding response from the United States,” he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, there will be no confidence in our national security, and under such circumstances, we will in no way unilaterally disarm.”
Although Ri repeated the well-known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “phased” approach to denuclearization, in which North Korea would be rewarded as it takes further steps, it struck that he did not a priori reject unilateral denuclearization, as Pyongyang did in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the very first summit between an active U.S. president and a North Korean leader on June 12 in Singapore, when Kim promised to work towards the “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees for North Korea’s security.
North Korea is aiming for a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal in a compelling way and even by objecting to the ‘declaration of the end of war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an air castle of the people who are unaware of us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions only strengthen our mistrust.”
Ri made no mention of plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, something the U.S. leader said earlier in the week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister emphasized three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If the other party to this issue of denuclearization was South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be a threat.
Yet the tone of Ri’s speech was significantly different from last year when he told the United Nations General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles on the U.S. mainland would be targeted after “Mr Evil President” Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened to completely destroy North Korea last year, praised Kim at the United Nations this year for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions should remain until North Korea denuclearizes.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this: “Whether it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia believe that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday: “The enforcement of Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and firmly until we have achieved full, definitive, verified denuclearization.”
Since 2006, the Security Council has unanimously imposed sanctions on North Korea to significantly reduce funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo had a meeting with Ri outside the UN General Assembly and said he would go back to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last visit did not go well.
Just hours after he left Pyongyang in July and said progress had been made, North Korea accused him of making “walking demands.”
North Korea vowed this month during a meeting with Moon to dismantle a missile site and also a nuclear complex if the United States were to take “appropriate measures.”
He said Kim had told him that the “appropriate measures” he wanted were security guarantees Trump had promised in Singapore, and steps toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students follow course on the importance of sufficient rest
A new course at Harvard University this year ensures that all students get more sleep, in an attempt to combat the growing macho culture in which it seems cool to study all night long while drinking lots of caffeine.
One professor noted that students from the world’s largest university often have no idea of the basic principles to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, professor of Sleep Medicine at Harvard Medical School, a specialist associated with Brigham and Women's Hospital, set up the course, which he knows is unique in the US.
He got the idea to start the course after giving a speech about the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of my speech, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only hearing this now, in my last year?’
She said no one had ever told her how important sleep is, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being organized for the first time this year, will explain to students the basic principles of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance and how they also promote their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university decided to organize the course when it was determined that students had severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The course lasts one hour and includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one of the sections, students see an image of a dormitory, where they click on coffee cups, curtains, exercise equipment, and books to learn more about the effects of caffeine and light, and the way sports performance is affected by sleep deprivation, and the importance of a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants are told how long-term sleep deprivation increases the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Using a campus map, with interactive icons, participants are encouraged to think about their daily routine.
“We know that with this we will not change the behavior of the students immediately.
But we think they have the right to know all this, just as people have the right to know what the consequences of choosing cigarettes are for their health, Czeisler added.
The culture of pride in studying overnight still exists, he says, and because of modern technology and increasing pressure on students, lack of sleep is an ever-increasing problem.
Providing adequate, good-quality sleep should be the student’s “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue, and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid weight gain because sleep deprivation causes the brain to give them a constant feeling of hunger.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old from Calfornia who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler to set up the course because he had taken classes with the professor last year when he was studying at Harvard in his first year.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to make the course available to everyone on campus.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all students to follow a similar study program before coming to the competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler advises students to set an alarm for their bedtime, and not just an alarm to get up. They should also be aware of the harmful effects of the ‘blue light’ of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, making it difficult for you to fall asleep.
