National Trust listens to the secret life of bats
New research being conducted on an estate in the Scottish Highlands is trying to reveal how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
The hope is that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and contribute to future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland, follows the common and small dwarf bat, the brown large-eared bat and the aquatic bat at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment is placed at key locations around the estate to follow the activities of the bats throughout the season.
NTS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using hand-held detectors.
Expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of the crayons of the bat and what kind does.
Then a map of the habitat and a report are produced to make a detailed picture on a landscape scale of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor at the NTS, hopes the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how they are used by the species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management, such as making pastures and how we can best maintain the forests for bats and similar species.
Flea populations in Scotland and the rest of the UK have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development activities that affect sleeping places and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lightning can also pose a risk, as can flycatchers and certain chemical treatments of building materials and attacks by domestic cats.
But bats are not really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching a prey.
They use an advanced echo-location technique to determine the position of insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The NTS has ten trained experts, who regularly investigate, inspect sleeping places and sometimes perform rescue operations.
The organisation has even set up the first and only bat reserve in Scotland at the Threave estate in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Landscaping manager David Thompson says the estate is the ideal territory for bats.
"Here at Threeave we have a great environment for bats," he said.
"We have the old buildings, lots of very old trees and the right habitat.
But so much about bats is not yet known, and that’s why the work we do here and elsewhere will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of controlling bats before maintenance work is carried out, as the possible unconscious destruction of a sleeping place could lead to the death of 400 female bats and their young, potentially wiping out a full local population.
Mice are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, trouble or disturb them or to destroy their sleeping places.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish officer for the Bat Conservation Trust, has asked the public to contribute to help.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and of many of our species we simply don’t know how their populations are doing.”
