Red glow update: Concentrations decrease in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Conservation Commission (Florida Commission for the Conservation of Fish and Fauna) shows a general decline in concentrations of Red Fever in parts of the Tampa Bay Area (located on the west coast of Florida in the U.S.).
According to the commission, there are reports of fragmentary increases in the red glow in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier, which could indicate a decrease in concentrations.
The red glow extends over an average of 200 km of coastline, from northern Pinellas to southern Lee counties.
There are about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County spots to see, but in fewer places than last week.
There was also a red glow in Pasco County.
Medium concentrations have been reported for the coast of Pinellas County in the past week, low to high concentrations for the coast of Hillsborough County, background to high concentrations in Manatee County, background to high concentrations at or near the coast of Sarasota County, background to high concentrations in Charlotte County, background to high concentrations at or near the coast of Lee County, and high concentrations at or near the coast of Lee County.
There are persistent reports of airway irritation in the provinces of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee, and Collier.
In northwest Florida, no reports of airway irritation were reported in the past week.
